---
description: Cursor Rules Location
globs: *.mdc
alwaysApply: true
---
# Cursor Rules Location

Rules for placing and organizing Cursor rule files in the repository.

<rule>
name: cursor_rules_location
description: Standards for placing Cursor rule files in the correct directory
filters:
  # Match any .mdc files
  - type: file_extension
    pattern: "\\.mdc$"
  # Match files that look like Cursor rules
  - type: content
    pattern: "(?s)<rule>.*?</rule>"

actions:
  - type: reject
    conditions:
      - pattern: "^(?!\\.\\/\\.cursor\\/rules\\/.*\\.mdc$)"
        message: "Cursor rule files (.mdc) must be placed in the .cursor/rules directory"

  - type: suggest
    message: |
      When creating Cursor rules:

      1. All rules MUST be placed in the /rules directory:
         ```
         .cursor/rules/
         ├── universal-rule.mdc
         ├── another-universal.mdc
         ├── local-rule.local.mdc
         └── another-local.local.mdc
         ```

      2. Determine if the rule should be universal or local:
         - Universal rules: Apply to all developers and should be committed to the repository
         - Local rules: Apply only to your local development environment

         If the rule is local, append .local to the filename:
         ```
         .cursor/rules/
         ├── universal-rule.mdc
         ├── another-universal.mdc
         ├── local-rule.local.mdc
         └── another-local.local.mdc
         ```

      3. Follow the naming convention:
         - Use kebab-case for filenames
         - Always use .mdc extension
         - For local rules, append .local before .mdc
         - Make names descriptive of the rule's purpose

      4. Directory structure:
         ```
         PROJECT_ROOT/
         ├── .cursor/
         │   └── rules/
         │       ├── universal-rule.mdc
         │       ├── local-rule.local.mdc
         │       └── ...
         └── ...
         ```

      5. Never place rule files:
         - In the project root
         - In subdirectories outside .cursor/rules
         - In any other location

examples:
  - input: |
      # Bad: Rule file in wrong location
      rules/my-rule.mdc
      my-rule.mdc
      .rules/my-rule.mdc

      # Good: Universal rule file in correct location
      .cursor/rules/my-rule.mdc

      # Good: Local rule file in correct location
      .cursor/rules/my-rule.local.mdc
    output: "Correctly placed Cursor rule file"

metadata:
  priority: high
  version: 1.0
</rule>
